<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 94 / O'Reilly submits Pounds 30m bid for stake in Independent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony O'Reilly, the Irish businessman and newspaper publisher, last night
increased the stakes in the increasingly bitter battle for the future of The
Independent newspaper by submitting a formal offer for up to 29.9 per cent
of the company.
The offer, worth in the region of Pounds 30m, has been assembled by
Charterhouse merchant bank and will be the only formal offer on the table
when the board of Newspaper Publishing, owner of The Independent, meets
today.
It is clear that the lossmaking Newspaper Publishing, which is in need of a
cash injection, could have a cheque for between Pounds 25m and Pounds 30m by
Friday, depending on the precise shareholding involved.
A consortium, including Mirror Group Newspapers and Mr Andreas Whittam
Smith, main founder of The Independent, which announced on Monday that it
intended to bid for the company, has not yet agreed a price and no formal
bid is expected before next week
The consortium, whose other members include existing Independent
shareholders El Pais of Spain and La Repubblica of Italy, is talking about
an offer in the region of Pounds 2 a share. This would value Newspaper
Publishing at around Pounds 40m. The proposed price would take into account
the injection of around Pounds 20m into the company to pay off debt of
around Pounds 5m and provide working capital and money to promote both The
Independent and The Independent on Sunday.
Mr O'Reilly, the chief executive of HJ Heinz, the international food
company, is chairman of Independent Newspapers of Ireland and a substantial
shareholder.
The offer may only be the opening shot in the battle. The O'Reilly camp has
made clear it is prepared to make a full bid for the paper. It is believed
the Dublin company has been approached by a large UK group not in the
newspaper business.
Mr Giles Elliott, of Schroders, the merchant bank which represents El Pais
and La Repubblica, said yesterday his clients would vote against an O'Reilly
offer.
MGN, which would under its proposal take a 40 per cent stake in Newspaper
Publishing, would offer help on everything from printing and distribution to
general management.
The journalists at The Independent have rejected the proposals of the
consortium mainly because of the involvement of MGN and its chief executive,
Mr David Montgomery.
</TEXT>
