<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equities Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Active selling, some of which was done through the use of sophisticated
derivative instruments, brought a sharp retreat but reduced volume in stock
index futures, writes Joel Kibazo.
A strong opening for the March futures contract on the FT-SE 100 Index at
3,494 seemed to indicate a firm session ahead. However, this was soon
undermined by selling from Salomon Brothers.
A host of other factors played a part in the day's decline. Aggressive
selling of the bund futures initiated a similar response in traders of
March, as did Tuesday's issuing of an OTC put option. US investment house
Goldman Sachs was also said to have issued a call and put warrant yesterday,
all of which dampened enthusiasm for the contract.
But it was the fall on Wall Street following poor US consumer confidence
figures that brought the sharpest decline of the day, sending March below
its recent support level of 3,460.
It closed at 3,448, down 30 from yesterday's close and at a 6-point discount
to its fair value premium to cash of about 7 points. Turnover at 9,721
contracts was one of the lowest in recent sessions.
The traded options sector was more buoyant and saw improved turnover of
46,833 lots, Volume in the FT-SE 100 option only showed a slight improvement
at 12,921 contracts.
Better than expected results from international trading group Lonrho brought
increased activity to the group's stock options. They headed the list of
active stock trades, finishing with a total of 4,617 lots dealt.
</TEXT>
