<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): IBM news, technical questions
hit Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks retreated yesterday as jitters over the market's technical
conditions proved more compelling than a fresh batch of corporate results,
writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 17.45 down at 3,895.34 and the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 dipped 1.05 to 470.92. The American SE composite shed
2.78 to 480.59 and the Nasdaq composite fell 4.26 to 786.39. NYSE volume
came to 326m shares.
The market opened with a slight decline, but losses mounted steadily until
mid-afternoon, when the Dow bottomed out with a 22-point deficit and began
to retrace some ground.
Those issues most closely tied to the economic cycle have prospered in
recent weeks, but many were hit hard yesterday by profit-taking. Caterpillar
declined Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 98 5/8 , Boeing Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars
43, Allied Signal Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 77 7/8 and Bethlehem Steel
Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 21 5/8 .
The negative sentiment reflected growing anxiety over the failure of the
broad market indices to keep pace with the Dow blue chip barometer, which is
heavily weighted towards the cyclicals. Analysts said the divergence might
be an indication that the bull market had gone past its peak.
Stocks drew scant support from the bond market or the day's economic news.
The benchmark 30-year government security was down  5/16 to 98 3/4 in late
trading.
Meanwhile, the Conference Board's January consumer confidence index, at
83.2, proved to be less bullish than forecast. The announcement of a 6.7 per
cent month-to-month rise in sales of existing single-family homes in
December was a more welcome development.
Shares in International Business Machines were highly volatile after the
company posted fourth-quarter earnings of 62 cents a share, in line with
expectations. At one point the stock had fallen nearly Dollars 3, after an
equivalent gain the previous day, but rebounded to close just Dollars  3/8
off at Dollars 58 1/4 after 10.1m shares traded.
Pharmaceutical issues were active, with health care reform expected to be a
central theme of President Bill Clinton's State of the Union speech
yesterday evening. Merck added Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 35 5/8 after
reporting better than expected operating income. Mylan Laboratories, a
generic drug supplier which could benefit from health care reform, climbed
Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 24 3/8 in spite of flat earnings.
Among the Dow components, American Express rose Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 32
3/4 after revealing late on Monday plans to spin off its Lehman Brothers
investment banking subsidiary.
Trading in Cooper Industries, an electrical and automobile equipment
supplier, was briefly suspended after it said a 25 per cent fall in 1994
earnings was possible. When reactivated, the stock plummeted to Dollars 41
1/2 , down Dollars 10 on the day.
On the Nasdaq, technology issues remained out of favour.
Canada
Toronto shares continued to retreat in fairly active trading amid cautious
profit-taking.
The TSE 300 index closed 9.6 off at 4,456.2 and falls led rises by 439 to
360 after volume of 66.4m shares valued at CDollars 842m.
</TEXT>
