<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / International Company News: Investors back Lorenzo plans for
US airline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Frank Lorenzo, the former US airline chief, yesterday renewed his efforts
to re-enter the industry by bringing in a group of investors to back his
plans to launch a low-cost carrier serving the US east coast.
He announced that Odyssey Partners, a private New York investment firm, and
other private investors had agreed to put Dollars 12.5m into ATX, formed to
promote his venture. His own stake would be diluted to less than 25 per
cent.
He also said ATX had chosen Mr Stephen Berger, an Odyssey partner, as its
first chairman. He is a former executive director of the Port Authority of
New York and New Jersey.
For months Mr Lorenzo has been trying to win a licence to start up a
no-frills, low-fare airline serving the east coast. He says the carrier will
offer unrestricted fares of Dollars 69 on the Baltimore-Boston and
Washington-Boston routes, compared with the current average of Dollars 129.
However, he is strongly opposed by the airline unions because of the bitter
confrontations when Mr Lorenzo headed Continental Airlines and Eastern
Airlines in the 1980s. Both companies eventually went bankrupt.
