<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Rowland to retain Lonrho shares until price
recovers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tiny Rowland said yesterday that he would not be a seller of his
remaining Lonrho shares until the market price reached between 250p and
350p.
Following yesterday's results, the share price moved in the right direction
for him, closing up 8p to 153p.
'Why should the shares not go back to the level of their pre-Maxwell days?',
he asked. In the months after Mr Robert Maxwell died in November 1991, there
was a sharp fall in the share prices of companies run by powerful
entrepreneurs such as Mr Rowland.
It was this plunge which allowed Lonrho's joint chief executive, Mr Dieter
Bock, to acquire an 18.8 per cent stake in the group at the beginning of
last year for an average price of less than 100p a share.
The important indicators of financial performance and balance sheet strength
improved at the company in the year to September 30. The ratio of debt to
equity fell from 57 per cent to 31 per cent. Net borrowings were Pounds 446m
(down from Pounds 849m a year earlier, thanks largely to disposals),
compared with net assets of Pounds 1.42bn.
Because of the diluting effect of last year's rights issue, net assets per
share were 138p, down from 158p. The company pointed out that its 45 per
cent shareholding in Ashanti Goldfields is valued in its balance sheet at
Pounds 89m, compared with a possible market value of more than Pounds 400m
when Ashanti is floated later this year.
Mr Bock said that Lonrho would not be selling any of its shares in the
flotation.
Over the past year, Mr Bock has reorganised Lonrho into four divisions:
mining, agriculture, hotels and general trade. There was an improving profit
performance from all of them.
Mining pushed up pre-tax profits by 60 per cent to Pounds 40m on turnover of
Pounds 335m (Pounds 313m); pre-tax profits from hotels rose from Pounds 1m
to Pounds 12m on Pounds 260m (Pounds 218m); general trade more than doubled
its contribution from Pounds 5m to Pounds 11m on Pounds 196m (Pounds 174m);
and there was a 50 per cent improvement in pre-tax earnings in the
agricultural division to Pounds 12m.
The group became even more dependent on Africa during the year. The
continent generated Pounds 69m of the Pounds 79m of pre-tax profits from
continuing operations against Pounds 44m a year earlier.
Capital expenditure is on a sharply declining trend. It was Pounds 121m,
down from Pounds 173m in 1992, and is forecast by the company at less than
Pounds 100m in the current year. Mr Bock said that the company had
eliminated most of its loss-making businesses.
However, last year's pre-tax profits were depressed by the legal costs of
the company's long running dispute with the Egyptian Fayed brothers - which
was settled in October - over the Fayed's 1985 purchase of House of Fraser
department stores. Lonrho's legal expenses were less than Pounds 5m in the
year justended, all of it charged against the profits of continuing
operations.
In the current financial period, there is likely to be a charge of around
Pounds 1.5m from payments to be made to four directors who are leaving the
company.
</TEXT>
