<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Was Rasputin a mad monk who liked to get his leg over? Or a misunderstood
softy who would always give the girls in his home village what they wanted?
Is there any difference between the two? Timewatch promises a revisionist
version of the Siberian peasant who had, supposedly, such influence on
Nicholas and Alexandra (8.00 BBC2). Even more sexually bizarre is American
artist Jeff Koons who takes pictures of his wife, the topless Italian MP
Cicciolina, doing the most amazing things to him with her tongue. He chooses
the John Hancock Centre in Chicago in Building Sights USA (8.50 BBC2).
The Day Today continues its appallingly accurate and consequently hilarious
spoof of television news (9.00 BBC2). Dispatches tries to discover whether
the agent causing BSE ('mad cow disease') could have passed into the human
food chain (9.00 C4).
In Middlemarch Ladislaw responds to Arthur Brooke's invitation to stay and
the Vincys are more desperate than ever to discover the details of old
Featherstone's will (9.30 BBC2).
</TEXT>
