<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Arms link to dam aid deal admitted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British and Malaysian ministers signed a protocol in 1988 tying defence
sales to civil aid projects, Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, said last
night, Kevin Brown and James Blitz writes.
Mr Hurd told the Commons in a written answer that the protocol was signed by
Mr George (now Lord) Younger, the then defence secretary, at the request of
the Malaysian government.
Mr Hurd said Lord Younger wrote to the Malaysian finance ministry in June
1988 to say that aid could not be linked to defence sales.
As a result the issue was not taken up in a memorandum of understanding on
defence procurement signed by Mrs Margaret (now Lady) Thatcher, the then
prime minister, in September 1988.
However, the admission that a formal link between defence sales and aid was
agreed between the two will add to the controversy over British aid to
Malaysia's Pergau dam project in the late 1980s.
The Commons foreign affairs committee is expected to decide today to go
ahead with an investigation into the project, which has cost the Exchequer
about Pounds 300m and has been described as a 'very bad buy' by Whitehall
officials.
Members of the committee said last night that an investigation would
certainly take place, and that the body simply had to decide how and when to
proceed.
The Commons public accounts committee has recently examined the project and
is due to release a report this year. Its findings will criticise the
government for spending more money than was necessary on the project, which
is expected to lead to a rise in Malaysian electricity prices.
</TEXT>
