<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / New mine operators warned of liabilities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Private mine operators wishing to take over former British Coal pits in the
Durham coalfield may face legal action from Durham County Council - unless
the government spells out where responsibility lies after privatisation for
abandoned mineworkings.
Mr Len James, chairman of the county council's environment committee, warned
yesterday that unless the coal industry privatisation bill specifies who is
responsible for the potential problems of minewater pollution, methane and
subsidence, his council may seek injunctions against any incoming private
operators in an attempt to force them to accept liability.
'Prospective purchasers could find their plans bogged down in a legal
quagmire while we continue to fight for what we believe is right,' said Mr
James.
The question of responsibility for coalmining's historic legacy affects many
mining areas of Britain, but is of immediate concern in County Durham which
is riddled with mineworkings dating back centuries. Minewater pumping, which
prevents pollution, has been costing British Coal Pounds 6m a year in that
area.
The Department of Trade and Industry said yesterday the bill covered the
environmental issues raised. British Coal yesterday won planning consent
from West Glamorgan county council for an 800-acre opencast mine overlooking
Neath Valley, south Wales. The mine, which will employ 140 people, is
expected to produce 3m tonnes of anthracite over nine years.
</TEXT>
