<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Chamber members to vote on merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plans for the merger of north-east England's three chambers of commerce to
create one of the UK's biggest chambers will be put to the vote next week.
Unveiling details of the proposal yesterday, the senior figures in all three
chambers stressed their support for the merger.
They believe a merger would strengthen the north-east's business voice and
enhance the services available to member companies while achieving economies
of scale.
The 100 members of the Tynedale Chamber have already backed the plans. On
Monday, extraordinary general meetings in Billingham and Gateshead will seek
the support of the 2,800 members of the Teesside and Tyne and Wear chambers.
If they agree, the merger will be completed by January 1995, creating one of
the five-largest chambers in the UK.
The new North East Chamber would have almost 3,000 members, from companies
such as ICI to individual entrepreneurs, and an annual turnover, including
training activities, of about Pounds 4m.
It would continue to be owned and run by its members and is expected to work
closely with the emerging national one-stop shop Business Links advice
network, championed by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary.
The three chambers' present 51 staff would continue to be employed by the
merged chamber. A new head office in Durham is planned, supported by
satellite offices based in Middlesbrough, Sunderland, Durham, South Tyneside
and Newcastle.
The chamber would also have a presence in several other locations in the
region. It is expected to seek help from the Department of Trade and
Industry towards the Pounds 224,000 restructuring costs.
The chief executive post for the new body would be advertised.
The proposed merger accords with the Association of British Chamber of
Commerce's strategy of creating a 'quality network' by forming larger
chambers.
At present, it has 110 member chambers in the UK, representing 85,000
businesses. Its aim is to reduce the number of chambers in the next few
years to about 50, through mergers and joint operational arrangements.
The proposed merger was described yesterday by Teesside Chamber president Mr
Brian Beaumont as 'the biggest single event in the long history of the three
chambers'.
Tyne and Wear Chamber traces its roots back to 1815, making it one of
Britain's oldest chambers.
Teesside's Chamber's origins lie in the Stockton-on-Tees Chamber, founded
131 years ago.
Tynedale, which covers part of Northumberland, was founded in 1984.
</TEXT>
<XX>
