<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Public-sector views 'harden' on pay freeze
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Opinion among public-sector workers has hardened in the past few weeks
against the government's public-sector pay bill freeze, according to union
leaders, who believe there is a danger of industrial conflict in the early
summer.
'Our members were subdued. Now they are saying we have had enough,' said one
senior union official.
But the unions are expected to drop their plan for a day of action on April
11, expected to be endorsed at a TUC meeting next Tuesday.
Instead they aim to gain public support through a long campaign focusing on
the lower-paid public-sector workers.
Union leaders yesterday called on the government to abandon the pay bill
freeze and honour the recommendations of the independent pay review bodies,
which cover 1.4m public sector workers, including nurses, teachers, doctors
and dentists, and the armed forces.
Review body reports for doctors and nurses - now with the government -
suggest rises of up to 3 per cent.
Members of the review bodies are in a politically sensitive position. They
must recommend what they believe public-service workers should be paid
compared with similar workers in the private sector, but they do not want
their reports to be rejected by the government.
Mr Rodney Bickerstaffe, associate general secretary of Unison, Britain's
biggest union, said: 'Any undue pressure or interference by ministers would
be a bitter betrayal of the review bodies' key role in keeping industrial
stability.'
He warned that there would be a backlash among nurses and other
public-service workers if the government tried to attach productivity
strings to their pay rises this year.
Ms Christine Hancock, general secretary of the Royal College of Nursing,
said: 'Nurses expect to be treated no differently over their pay than
members of parliament who received 2.7 per cent this year.'
Nurses, midwives and health visitors are seeking pay rises of up to 10 per
cent.
Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, accused the government yesterday of
making up its policy of freezing the public-sector pay bill 'on the hoof'.
'The policy as it stands blatantly discriminates against public-sector
workers,' Mr Monks said. 'It will create enormous problems with retention of
staff and recruitment and widen the pay gap between different grades, not to
mention the effect on morale.'
He added: 'We will see a massive pay gulf opening up between the public and
private sectors. The policy is just not sustainable.'
The Institute of Directors called on the government yesterday to abolish
national pay bargaining for the public sector. 'It is the last vestige of
the corporate state and should be swept away,' said the institute's policy
director Mrs Ann Robinson.
'It is no longer appropriate that teachers and nurses are paid exactly the
same throughout the country on a national pay scale,' she added.
</TEXT>
