<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Fimbra call over watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A call for people who work in the financial services industry to be fully
involved in the proposed new retail financial services watchdog came
yesterday from one of the regulators it is to replace.
The council of Fimbra, the self-regulatory organisation for independent
financial advisers, said it was 'vital' that there should be proper
involvement by practitioners, in the interests of investor protection.
The statement is a modest boost for the planned personal investment
authority, since Fimbra does not take issue with the proposal that only nine
of the 19-strong PIA board should be practitioners.
Independent financial advisers, who make up Fimbra, have been among the most
outspoken critics of the PIA proposals, arguing that in their current state
they do not represent self-regulation.
At the same time, however, the statement offers a clear warning about the
sort of structure Fimbra wants to see the PIA adopt.
It urges strongly that practitioners should be fully involved in committees
and working parties which report directly to the PIA board.
This reflects unease within the IFA sector that the PIA may be an
'executive-driven' regulator - closer to the model of the Securities and
Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, than to Lautro, the
self-regulatory organisation for the life insurance industry, where
committees play a greater role.
The PIA board will meet today to discuss its draft prospectus and
application to be recognised as a regulator.
Squabble, Page 21
