<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Smith calls for interest rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, yesterday called for an immediate cut in
interest rates to reduce the risk of the recovery being choked off by
impending tax increases.
Speaking in Bonn he urged the government to co-ordinate further interest
rate reductions with Britain's European Union partners.
'This is particularly important in Britain where the Conservative government
are forcing through massive tax increases which even the chancellor of the
exchequer now admits will check the recovery,' he said.
Addressing a 'Euro-conference' staged by Germany's SPD social democratic
party, Mr Smith argued that the consequences of allowing recovery to falter
were 'too serious to contemplate'.
He said: 'The cohesion of our own communities is at stake. Recession and
economic decline are clearly the breeding ground of crime, intolerance and
racism.
'Europe cannot afford a downward spiral that would threaten not just our
prosperity but our democratic way of life.'
As MPs at Westminster began considering the finance bill implementing
chancellor Mr Kenneth Clarke's first Budget, Mr Smith said the issues of
jobs, investment and growth were back at the top of the economic agenda
'where they always should have been'.
But he urged his audience not to let the right dominate the debate about
jobs 'as they did over inflation in the 1980s'.
Signalling one likely theme of Labour's European election campaign in June
Mr Smith said there was a clear 'jobs battleground' ahead.
'It is a choice between a high-wage, high-tech, high-skilled route to the
highest possible levels of employment and the Conservatives' low-paid,
low-skilled, insecure, unsafe, deregulated economics of the sweatshop.'
What was needed for Europe to prosper was a 'self-confident, adaptable,
highly skilled and participative workforce,' Mr Smith said.
'None of these qualities will be present in a sweatshop economy that drives
down wages, removes employment rights and relies on fear to provide
flexibility at the workplace.'
Touching on what has recently been a favourite subject of the Conservatives
Mr Smith said economic recovery was also necessary for the EU to fulfil its
wider responsibilities by doing 'all that we can to help the people of
eastern and central Europe'.
</TEXT>
