<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Training standards body launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A business-led body called Investors in People UK was launched yesterday to
boost national promotion of the IIP standard, which seeks to link training
to the business needs of companies.
The organisation is financially supported by the government and is chaired
by Sir Brian Wolfson, chairman of Wembley, which owns the north London
stadium.
Board members include Mr John Adstead, personnel director of J. Sainsbury,
Mr Terry Morgan, managing director of Land Rover, and Mr Leif Mills, general
secretary of Bifu, the banking union.
The standard, which has been developed by the government, is promoted by
training and enterprise councils and their Scottish equivalents, local
enterprise companies, which also validate whether a company has reached the
appropriate levels of training and staff development to attain IIP. The new
body will seek to ensure that uniform stand ards of assessment are set.
To be recognised, an employer must make a public commitment to employee
development so that staff can achieve the business objectives of the
organisation, regularly review the training and development needs of all of
its employees, and then evaluate the effectiveness of training.
Management, Page 11
