<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Marine insurers report improvement in results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rises in insurance rates paid by shipowners have led to an improvement in
the results of London-based insurance companies specialising in marine
insurance.
The Institute of London Underwriters, which provides services to 74 London
marine and aviation companies, said yesterday that its marine underwriters
were experiencing the strongest upturn in rates for many years.
Yet it warned that it would be some time before profitability was restored,
following severe price competition and heavy losses in recent years.
At least 18 companies withdrew from the market last year. The institute said
40 members had resigned since 1990.
Mr Peter Evans, the institute's chairman, said: 'The London market is
undergoing a transformation on a scale never seen before and at a speed hard
to comprehend.'
Institute companies - which account on the same three-year basis as Lloyd's
 -said preliminary figures showed a strong rise in profitability last year.
Premium income registered for hull business increased from Pounds 361m in
the first year of the three-year 1991 account, to Pounds 624.2m for the
first year of the 1993 account. In the same period hull claims rose to
Pounds 63.5m from Pounds 60.5m. Underwriters saw a similar improvement in
cargo and aviation business.
Last year saw a sharp drop in marine casualties, with 121 vessels of 500
tonnes or more lost, compared with 134 in 1992.
The value of ships lost in 1993 is expected to exceed the 1992 figure of
Dollars 590m, when figures are finally confirmed.
Aviation underwriters have also increased premium levels. Total losses of
western-built jet airliners fell from 26 in 1992 to 22 in 1993, but the
value of claims rose to Dollars 433m (Dollars 432m). Partial losses rose to
42 (Dollars 302m) in 1993 from 26 (Dollars 112m) in 1992.
</TEXT>
