<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Independent chiefs consider auction as last resort
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An auction for Newspaper Publishing, owner of The Independent and the
Independent on Sunday, has not been ruled out if satisfactory bids are not
received soon, Raymond Snoddy writes.
Mr Ian Hay Davison, chairman of the loss-making newspaper publisher, is
becoming increasingly exasperated by the delay in receiving a formal bid for
the company from the consortium put together by Mr Andreas Whittam Smith,
the main founder of The Independent.
Pressure is being put on the consortium, which includes Mirror Group
Newspapers, to submit a bid as soon as possible.
Mr Tony O'Reilly, chairman of Independent Newspapers of Ireland, is likely
to submit a counterbid soon after this, possibly with another newspaper
group.
If the process becomes so delayed that the future of the titles is
threatened, a clear option for the non-executive directors would be to hold
an auction, although that would be seen as a last resort.
