<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Mirror trial delayed by settlement talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Trustees for the Mirror Group Newspapers Pension Scheme were last night
trying to agree an out-of-court deal with securities firms from which they
are seeking Pounds 175m in allegedly misappropriated assets and damages.
The funds are part of the more than Pounds 440m of pension assets which
disappeared from schemes controlled by the late Mr Robert Maxwell.
The talks have delayed the start of a civil trial which was set to start in
the High Court yesterday. Invesco MIM, Capel-Cure Myers Capital Management,
Lehman Brothers International and Credit Suisse are named in the case. The
individual position of each of the defendants was unclear last night.
It is understood, however, that Lehman Brothers, which is separately the
subject of a Pounds 77m writ from liquidators for Bishopsgate Investment
Management, the Maxwell-owned fund management company, had been discussing a
possible settlement in that case. Lehman Brothers, while insisting that it
believes it has a strong case, has said it is only interested in a global
settlement embracing all legal actions against it and involving all the
financial institutions against whom the pension schemes have made claims.
Sir Peter Walker, appointed by the government to mediate between the
parties, is seeking a global settlement involving agreements between all the
schemes and all the banks.
Last night's talks were aimed at averting a trial expected to last six
months and to cost several million pounds in legal fees. Both sides are
anxious to avoid a trial because of the adverse publicity for the financial
institutions and the fear of squandering scarce pension assets on legal
fees.
The trial is due to start today.
</TEXT>
