<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Portillo seeks to repel Labour's tax attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour's campaign to discredit the Conservative party's claim to be the
party of low taxation would boomerang by the time of the next general
election, Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, forecast in
the Commons last night.
He told jeering Labour MPs that while they were 'sitting pretty' now they
would not be feeling so clever when they had to face the voters with their
plans for increasing public spending on health, education and other
projects.
Mr Portillo, moving the second reading of the Finance Bill implementing the
Budget proposals, insisted: 'There is an unbreakable link between what
governments spend and what they must raise in taxation'.
He met a barrage of protests from Labour MPs when, like Mr John Major, the
prime minister, he refused to accept that the Conservatives had won the last
general election on a false prospectus, involving promises of further tax
cuts.
Mr Portillo condemned the refusal of Labour leaders to follow normal
practice by negotiating a voluntary timetable for the discussion of the bill
 -the longest introduced to the Commons since the second world war - and
left little doubt that the government would use the parliamentary guillotine
to curtail debate on its line-by-line committee stage consideration.
Ms Harriet Harman, Labour's shadow chief secretary, said in a hard-hitting
speech that the bill increased 12 significant taxes and represented a
historic moment.
It marked a decisive turning point against the Conservative party, clearly
demonstrating that its pledges on tax cuts had been betrayed. To Labour
cheers she told Conservative MPs that their integrity 'lies in tatters' and
that they had nothing left.
She firmly rebuffed Tory backbenchers who challenged her indictment by
quoting the promises to cut taxes which they made to their own constituents.
Ms Harman called on Tory backbenchers who had attacked the imposition of VAT
on domestic fuel to vote for a Labour amendment to the bill which sought to
remove it.
Mr Portillo argued that it was the natural instinct of the Conservative
party to control public expenditure and reduce taxation while, in sharp
contrast, Labour had a perpetual desire to increase spending and raise
taxes.
He said: 'Nothing since the last election changes the validity of that
choice put before the British people.'
Appealing to the loyalty of Tory backbenchers, Mr Portillo warned: 'Our
recovery will depend on a clear, sustained determination to take difficult
decisions now in order to provide the basis for long-term prosperity'.
Pressed about the impact of the tax increases imposed by the bill on the
economy, he endorsed the judgment of Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, that
the recovery now in progress was strong enough to be proof against them.
Mr Portillo acknowledged that the extension of value added tax to domestic
fuel had been 'a most difficult decision' and thanked Tory backbenchers for
supporting it.
</TEXT>
