<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Dedicated follower of fashion: The trend away from full-time
employment paints a misleading picture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sock Shop's decision to move most of its staff from full-time to part-time
contracts is part of an increasing trend in both the retail sector and the
economy as a whole.
It is also contributing to the rather misleading impression of buoyancy in
the jobs market. The net effect of Sock Shop replacing full-time staff with
part-time staff will be to increase the number of jobs in the economy, but
the number of hours worked will be static and might even fall.
Exactly the same effect was produced a year ago when Burton Group shed 2,000
full-time jobs and replaced them with about 3,000 part-time positions. Other
big retailers, such as BHS and the Allied Maples Group, have taken similar
steps and about a third of all retail staff are now estimated to be
part-timers.
Campaigners complain that this shift allows the government to claim that new
jobs are being created when in fact, adjusting for the increase in part-time
work, there is no net job creation at all.
Mr Paul Convery of the Unemployment Unit said: 'All that is happening is
that full-time jobs are being repackaged as less secure part-time jobs which
is actually bad for the economy as a whole in terms of consumer confidence.'
The figures do lend some support to this argument. According to the Labour
Force Survey - the most authoritative source on employment trends - there
was an overall increase of 67,000 in the number of people in work between
winter 1992-93 and summer 1993, from 21.18m to 21.25m.
But over the same period the number of full-time jobs fell by 38,000 and the
number of part-time jobs grew by 105,000.
Adjusting for the move to part-time working, the number of new 'full-time
equivalent' jobs was only just more than 3,000 - not 67,000. And over the
same period the average weekly hours worked fell from 36.4 to 36.3.
There are several incentives for employers to switch employees to part-time
working. It can create genuine increases in flexibility allowing more staff
in shops, for example, at busy times and fewer when they are not needed. It
can also be popular with some employees.
However, cost-saving is the crucial factor for most companies. Any employee
who works less than 15 hours per week, or earns less than Pounds 56, does
not have to be covered for National Insurance. As soon as that threshold is
reached, then National Insurance has to be paid on all the hours worked.
Any employee who works less than 16 hours per week does not qualify for
employment protection or for any statutory benefits such as redundancy pay
and maternity benefit. For these reasons the trend towards switching from
full-time to part-time work is likely to continue, and with it the
statistical impression that all is well in the labour market.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Sock Shop Holdings.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
