<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Labour steps up attack on 'bizarre' judicial reform plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday moved to exploit the government's embarrassment over its
troubled police and courts legislation by accusing Mr Michael Howard, home
secretary, of trying to undermine the independence of the judicial system.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, said the bill would change fundamental
constitutional rights by increasing central government control of police
authorities and magistrates' courts, and abolishing the so-called right to
silence.
In a wide-ranging attack on government policy delivered in a speech at the
London School of Economics, Mr Blair confirmed that a future Labour
government would incorporate the European Convention on Human Rights into
British law.
This would allow people to take cases direct to the European Court of Human
Rights rather than going through the UK courts and then waiting for the
European Court to hear an appeal.
He said the police and courts bill, which was widely criticised during its
second reading in the Lords, was a panicky reaction to the 'patent failure'
of the government's law-and-order policies.
'The Tory party is desperate and the dangers are plain. Policy is formulated
in panic, announced without thought and pushed through with only the next
day's headlines as a guiding principle,' he said.
Mr Blair said provisions allowing the home secretary to appoint five of 16
members of freshly constituted police authorities, including the chairman,
amounted to 'a dramatic change' to policing.
He said Mr Howard's plan to put magistrates' court clerks on fixed contracts
linked to performance criteria set by the Home Office had 'spread alarm and
despondency'.
Mr Blair also criticised plans in the criminal justice bill to require
judges to demonstrate the unwillingness of defendants to answer police
questions by calling them to the witness box.
He said the 'bizarre' proposals, which conflict with the recommendations of
the royal commission on criminal justice, would 'compromise the judiciary in
a wholly unacceptable way'. The provisions have also been criticised by Lord
Taylor, the Lord Chief Justice.
Mr Howard is expected to water down the police and courts bill by giving
police authorities the freedom to choose a chairman, and by strengthening
protection of the independence of magistrates' clerks. However, it is
unclear whether this will be enough to overcome the criticism, led by
prominent Tories including Lord Whitelaw, the former deputy prime minister.
</TEXT>
