FT  26 JAN 94 / Algerian conference snub
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Algeria's leading political parties yesterday boycotted the first day of a
conference for national reconciliation called by the country's High State
Council, writes Francis Ghiles.
The two-day meeting aims to end the violence which over the past two years
has claimed over 3,500 lives and is also set to approve a new collective
presidency to replace the body which has ruled Algeria since elections were
cancelled in January 1992.
The Islamic Salvation Front, which was poised to win the election, dismissed
the idea of dialogue with those who had 'stopped the electoral process and
spilt the blood of Moslem people'. The leader of the lay opposition party,
the Front des Forces Socialistes, Mr Hocine Ait Ahmed, said any head of
state appointed by the conference would have no legitimacy.
