FT  26 JAN 94 / Nigeria unrest hits oil profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Oil companies in Nigeria estimate losses in production and equipment of
about Dollars 200m (Pounds 133m) last year through civil disruptions and
protests against loss of land, pollution and inadequate living conditions,
writes Paul Adams in Lagos.
Shell, which produces half of Nigeria's quota of 1.8m barrels a day,
recorded 108 attacks or stoppages with the loss of 12m barrels in 1993. Agip
and Elf have reported smaller losses.
Nigeria's oil minister, Mr Don Etiebet, said at the weekend that the
government was considering tax concessions to the oil companies for
developing the local communities.
But this month's budget is not helping to encourage investment. The
introduction of a fixed rate of foreign exchange has doubled the cost of
bringing in capital.
