<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Call for Islamic economic co-operation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TEHRAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iran's president said yesterday economic co-operation between the 10 Islamic
members of the Economic Co-operation Organisation in the Middle East and
central Asia could reduce political tensions affecting them, Reuter reports
from Tehran.
President Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani was opening a meeting of the foreign
ministers of the 10 states that include Pakistan, Turkey, Afghanistan and
six former Soviet republics.
ECO was founded by neighbours Turkey, Iran and Pakistan in the 1950s as a
regional trading bloc but was largely dormant until it was expanded two
years ago to become the largest non- Arab Islamic organisation stretching
from Europe to China.
