FT  26 JAN 94 / Surprise interest rate cut boosts markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of Spain yesterday sent the markets soaring and bolstered the
peseta with a surprise quarter-point rate cut that brought the benchmark
intervention rate down to 8.75 per cent, writes Tom Burns in Madrid. The cut
came as unions planned to bring the country to a standstill in a 24-hour
general strike tomorrow.
The move apparently reflected confidence by the monetary authorities that
domestic recession has bottomed out, that headline inflation, which stood at
4.9 per cent last month, will fall to 3.5 per cent later this year and that
currency turmoils are unlikely in coming months.
The Madrid Bolsa index, which has been gaining in the past months, rose to a
record 343.81 high before easing to close at 342.94, up from 339.01 on
Monday. The peseta, under pressure following the Banesto bank crisis, had by
late afternoon strengthened to Pta80.93 to the D-Mark.
