<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 94 / Bonn agrees Telekom and post sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The way has been cleared for the privatisation of Germany's telecoms and
postal services after the liberal Free Democrats (FDP), the junior party in
the Bonn coalition, abandoned demands that the postal monopoly should be
broken up for the sale.
The privatisation bill for Deutsche Telekom, the national telecoms operator,
the German postal services and the Postbank, now has the formal backing of
all German parties, including the opposition Social Democrats (SPD). The SPD
votes are needed for the bill to pass through parliament. A first reading is
scheduled for next week.
The Free Democrats had earlier insisted that the privatisation bill should
specify when the monopolies of the postal services and of the telephone
infrastructure would end. However, the bill will specify that Deutsche
Telekom will lose its monopoly only on telephone voice services on January
1, 1998, to comply with a European Union decision to liberalise voice
telephony by this date. There will be no other reference to the status of
the monopolies in the bill.
The SPD has fiercely opposed the break-up of the loss-making postal services
mainly because of worries about job losses. The FDP, however, had argued
that competition should be introduced across the sector, implying the
stripping out of some of the profitable areas such as freight. The
government is hoping the bill will be adopted by the summer so that the law
could come into force at the beginning of 1995. This would in turn allow
Deutsche Telekom to raise much-needed cash for investment and to reduce its
DM100bn (Pounds 38bn) debt by selling a first tranche of shares in 1996.
However, the liberals and the dominant Christian Democrats (CDU) seem to
have reached an informal agreement for the partial liberalisation of the
postal monopoly at a later date. Mr Rainer Funke, state secretary in the
justice ministry and liberal MP responsible for the privatisation bill, said
that Mr Wolfgang Botsch, the post and telecoms minister, could decide
independently to liberalise postal services other than regular mail.
A letter by Chancellor Helmut Kohl to Quelle, Germany's largest mail-order
company, promising that the post monopoly will be broken, has already sent
shock waves through the German post agency.
A committee of independent experts is now studying the feasibility of
introducing competition in the postal services for packages, express mail
and other services other than regular letters. The German postal service has
warned that such a move would result in a yearly loss of DM3.4bn. But
sources in the post ministry say the post would only lose DM500m.
</TEXT>
