<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / International Company News: Gains from sale of investments
helps CGIP to maintain profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Capital gains from the sale of investments should allow CGIP, the French
holding company, to report steady profits for 1993, according to Mr
Ernest-Antoine Seilliere, the group chairman.
Mr Seilliere described 1993 as a difficult year. But during an interview he
said that 'after taking into account a net capital gain of FFr150m (Dollars
25.68m) from disposals made in the course of the year, we will maintain
without doubt our profit compared with 1992'. Then, CGIP reported net
profits of FFr542.6m.
The disposals made during the year included a 2.5 per cent stake in Valeo,
the vehicle components group, and 4.4 per cent of Cap Gemini Sogeti, the
computer services group.
The holding company has rebuilt its reserves through a convertible bond
issue at the beginning of this month. The issue, which raised about FFr1bn,
was aimed at strengthening the group's balance sheet following a number of
acquisitions and an increase in its stake in CarnaudMetalBox, the
Anglo-French packaging group, from 25.3 per cent to just over 32 per cent.
Mr Seilliere ruled out the possibility of a merger between the holding
company and the packaging group. 'CGIP is evolving in a logic of control
which is favourable to our shareholders. The hypothesis of a merger is not
envisaged' he said.
He said that a decision on the group's dividend would be taken by the
shareholders' assembly in June. 'Between now and then we will have a clearer
view of the development of our investments which, we hope, will allow us to
continue our policy of distribution.' he said.
CGIP, which paid a dividend of FFr32 in 1992, has generally increased its
dividend payments.
</TEXT>
