<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Japanese stock market plunges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS and EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japanese share prices plunged yesterday amid fears of turmoil after the
defeat of political reform bills initiated by Prime Minister Morihiro
Hosokawa.
The Nikkei index of 225 leading shares fell 954.19 points, or 4.9 per cent,
the largest single-day drop since August 1991, as shaken investors and
dealers rushed to unload their holdings.
Investors were also worried that political difficulties might further delay
the government's ability to stimulate the stumbling economy. The Keidanren,
the leading business federation, called on Mr Hosokawa not to call a snap
general election. Prolonged political uncertainty would further damage the
economy, warned Mr Gaishi Hiraiwa, the Keidanren's chairman.
Parliamentary officials of the ruling seven-party coalition met members of
the opposition Liberal Democratic party to try to form a joint panel of the
upper and lower houses as a forum for compromise. They plan to meet again
today.
The LDP blamed 'co-ordination' difficulties. The party is divided between a
minority who seek a watered-down version of the political reform plans - the
leadership's official line - and a majority who have strong reservations
over the proposed abandonment of Japan's multi-seat constituency system.
In one small sign of possible progress, the leadership of the Social
Democratic party, the largest coalition partner, said it was ready to meet
the LDP.
If, as is likely, Mr Hosokawa fails to get an agreement by the end of the
present parliamentary session on Saturday at midnight, the bills will
expire. Mr Hosokawa will then be under pressure to carry out his implied
promise to resign, although he is Japan's most popular politician.
Political observers believe that if Mr Hosokawa does resign, he would hand
over the prime ministership to a leading member of the seven-party
coalition, rather than call an election.
Mr Tsutomu Hata, foreign minister and leader of the Japan Renewal party, set
up last June by defectors from the LDP, or Mr Masayoshi Takemura, leader of
the New Harbinger party, another former LDP splinter group, are thought to
be front runners for the job.
On the Tokyo stock market, traders expect further turbulence this week due
to the uncertainty surrounding Mr Hosokawa's efforts to formulate a
compromise out of the reform bills by Saturday. 'There's no knowing how much
the market could fall if Mr Hosokawa is forced to resign,' warned Mr Takashi
Kanasaki, a director at Yamaichi Securities.
On the foreign exchange, political worries also prompted selling of the yen
against the dollar. It closed Y0.80 down against the dollar at Y112.10.
Vehicle output behind US, Page 4 World stocks, Page 38
</TEXT>
