<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Minister raps council over Tupe obstacle to contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The environment department yesterday ruled that a local authority had acted
anti-competitively when it refused to disclose details of its workforce's
pay and conditions to a private company bidding for a contract. The council
believed that the Transfer of Undertakings (Public Employees) regulations,
known as Tupe, applied to the contract, which meant that the bidder would be
obliged to accept the workforce on its existing terms and conditions. The
council insisted that Tupe terms would apply, but refused to say what they
were.
Yesterday's decision by the environment minister, Mr Tony Baldry, signals a
crackdown on councils' use of the regulations. He said: 'I am determined to
ensure that the treatment of Tupe by local authorities should not stand in
the way of fair competition.'
Langbaurgh-on-Tees Borough Council will now have to re-tender the contract.
Three other authorities, the London borough of Redbridge, Southampton City
Council and Bassetlaw District Council, have also been issued with statutory
notices asking them to explain their actions in awarding work to their own
labour force in possible breach of competitive tendering rules, following
allegations of anti-competitive behaviour in their treatment of Tupe.
</TEXT>
