<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Frankfurt and Paris move from
weakness to strength
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The outstanding feature yesterday was the move from weakness to strength in
both Frankfurt and Paris, writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT dug itself out of Friday's depression, but not before the Dax
index had fallen nearly 40 points to a morning low of 2,035.76. Worries
about possibly negative M3 and inflation indicators weighed it down, said Mr
Nigel Longley at Commerzbank in Frankfurt.
However, sentiment was rescued by January inflation figures from North Rhine
Westphalia which, at 3.3 per cent per annum, were slower than expected. The
Dax moved to an official close of 2,080.01, up a token 4.40, and carried on
climbing in the post bourse to end at an Ibis-indicated 2,107.29, 3.5 per
cent above its nadir.
Turnover fell from DM13.7bn to DM10.5bn. At the official close there were
more significant losses than gains among blue chips, but the rising dollar
brought strength to the big three chemical stocks, where Bayer led with a
gain of DM8.50 to DM351.50.
Elsewhere, Siemens rose DM9.60 to DM715 with its weak profits news
apparently digested and the pharmaceuticals group, Schering, put on DM42, or
4 per cent to DM1,065 on its BetaSeron prospects, and after a fall from a
1993/94 high of DM1,188.50.
All this compensated for weakness in banks, depressed by their rights
issues, and in automotive stocks. After hours, the March Dax future closed
39.5 higher at 2,129, and US buying took Bayer and Siemens further ahead, to
DM358 and DM721 respectively.
PARIS closed the account on a high note on lingering hopes that the Bank of
France might make a small cut in interest rates this morning. Support for
companies which have recently reported 1993 results also contributed to the
improved sentiment which lifted the CAC-40 index by 30.52, or 1.4 per cent
to 2,274.49.
Turnover was firm at FFr5.4bn.
Among the day's most actives UAP rose FFr43 or 7 per cent to FFr650 after
the insurer made a favourable estimate for 1993 and said that it was seeking
to expand into the UK in an effort to increase its market share.
St Gobain continued to firm following last week's good earnings news, the
shares adding another FFr22 or 3.3 per cent to FFr686, while Bouygues firmed
FFr18 to FFr733 ahead of today's results.
Both Euro Disney and Eurotunnel performed well, the former gaining FFr1.45
to FFr37.35 and the latter FFr2.05 to FFr51.95, lifted by news that the UK
government had confirmed the route of the fast rail link from London to the
Channel ports.
AMSTERDAM built on Friday's advance and the AEX index pushed briefly through
the 430 level during the session before settling back to close 1.23 higher
at 429.75.
Good gains continued to be achieved by the heavily weighted stocks, such as
Royal Dutch, up Fl 1.60 at Fl 213.60. However, there was also strong
activity elsewhere as investors digested positive news. Polygram, for
instance, rose during the session to an all-time high on reports that it was
involved in discussions to establish a new music-video television channel.
The shares finally closed up Fl 1.90 at Fl 80.10.
Fokker also went higher on reports that it had secured a Fl 250m contract to
supply aircraft to a French airline, with the shares ending up Fl 1.50 to Fl
23.50.
MILAN recouped Friday's losses on strength in the industrial sector. The
Comit index improved 4.30 to 617.90.
Montedison led the rise, gaining 1.9 per cent to L1,015 as hopes resurfaced
for a recovery in this sector. Olivetti also benefited from renewed hopes
that it would win the second cellular telecom licence to be awarded later
this year, the shares putting on L79 to L2,358.
Fiat was another of the day's gainers with suggestions that it might sell
one of its divisions - Snia being mentioned. The carmaker added L66 to
L4,510, and Snia L43 to L1,605.
ZURICH recovered from early weakness to close steady, but in very limited
trading, the SMI index closing 2.5 higher at 3,041.8.
MADRID eased across the board after hitting a succession of all-time highs
last week, the general index falling 2.29 to 339.01 in turnover of
Pta33.9bn.
In banks, BCH lost Pta80, or 2.5 per cent to Pta3,085 in volume of over
900,000 shares.
DUBLIN was pulled back by a bout of profit-taking following the market's
strong forward movement since the beginning of the year, said Mr Adrian
O'Carroll at Dillon Read. The ISEQ index closed down 17.98 at 2,049.48.
ATHENS continued its recovery after last week's corrections, the general
index closing 27.46 higher at 1,176.83; but brokers were not sure of its
next move, saying that there was support at 1,150, and resistance at 1,200.
ISTANBUL tumbled by nearly 7 per cent as the central bank continued to raise
short-term borrowing rates to defend the lira against the dollar. The
composite index ended at a provisional 24,260.75, down 1,812.17. Written and
edited by William Cochrane and John Pitt.
