<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Metals analysts very sceptical
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING,
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Analysts at a seminar in London yesterday were very sceptical about the
attempts being made to cut aluminium output and their potential impact on
the market.
'Unless consumers are given a very clear indication of what is actually
going to happen in the way of cuts and they are given specific details about
who is going to cut where and when, market sentiment will not change,' said
Mr Ted Arnold of Merrill Lynch.
Mr Neil Buxton of Metal Bulletin Research suggested annual cuts of 1.5m
tonnes were 'totally beyond the industry's reach.' He added: 'I would be
very surprised if there can be agreement on cuts of that size.'
Mr Simon Hunt of Brook Hunt Associates told the 1994 metals market forecasts
seminar, organised by Metal Bulletin and the FutureSource consultancy, that
an agreement might be reached but it would not last long. 'We think an
agreement will be cobbled together but it will not have teeth and in three
months time people will perceive it has no teeth. Meanwhile, the investment
funds will drive up prices and producers will say: Why do we have to cut?'
There were a number of factors working against an aluminium agreement, he
said. European producers were under less pressure because they had been
reducing costs and were now probably breaking even at Dollars 1,100 to
Dollars 1,150 a tonne compared with last night's unchanged three-month price
of Dollars 1,189.50. Also, it was unlikely that Moscow could control the
actions of smelters in remote Siberia. And 'not all the world's aluminium
producers believe this is the best way to deal with the problem of
oversupply.'
However, if there was a 10 per cent reduction in world production (excluding
Alcoa and Alcan which had already made deep cuts) stocks would fall by
700,000 tonnes this year and by 1.5m tonnes in 1995, Mr Hunt suggested.
Without cuts, total industry stocks would rise by 1m tonnes to 6.1m this
year and to 6.3m in 1995, compared with annual western demand of about 16m
tonnes.
</TEXT>
