<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / International Capital Markets: Turkish bank in US private
placement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bankers Trust has completed a Dollars 65m US private placement of
certificates backed by credit card receivables serviced by Interbank, the
private Turkish bank.
It is the first time that any Turkish borrower other than the Republic has
tapped the US market and follows a similar offering in the Eurobond market
in 1992, also arranged by Bankers Trust, according to Mr Rahmi Sayder,
vice-president of BT's European asset-backed securities group.
The certificates are issued by Interbank/AKK Trust, a special purpose
vehicle, which has purchased the right to receivables of Eurocard,
MasterCard and Visa credit cards used by foreign tourists and business
travellers in Turkey.
Interbank's wholly owned subsidiary, Anadolu Kredi Karti (AKK), is a market
leader in international credit card processing in Turkey.
The credit card receivables deal allows Interbank to secure medium-term
funding: the deal has a final maturity of five years and a four-year average
life. Bankers Trust declined to disclose the coupon or yield spread paid on
the fixed-rate securities.
The certificates, rated A by US rating agency Duff &amp; Phelps, were placed
with US institutions such as insurance companies, Mr Sayder said.
He added that similar structures, using credit card or other receivables
such as trade receivables, could be used in other countries, for example in
Greece and Eastern Europe. 'This is a great way of mobilising assets which
are not being used,' he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
