<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / International Company News: Boeing parades twin-engine
widebody
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Boeing's new 777 twin-engine widebody airliner, photographed here for the
first time, has just made its maiden ground voyage - across the factory
floor of Boeing's huge Everett facility north of Seattle.
The formal roll-out of the completed aircraft will take place in April with
first delivery to United Airlines in May 1995.
The 777, with a price tag of around Dollars 130m, is the biggest twin-engine
widebody ever developed, at a cost of around Dollars 4bn. It is powered by a
new generation of very large thrust engines developed by General Electric
and Pratt &amp; Whitney of the US and the UK Rolls-Royce group.
The aircraft, with seating capacity ranging from 320 to more than 400
passengers depending on cabin configuration, is challenging the Airbus A340
four engine and Airbus A330 twin-engine widebody airliners as well as the
McDonnell Douglas three engine MD11.
Boeing has won 147 firm orders for the 777 and options for an additional 108
since the programme was launched in October 1990.
</TEXT>
