<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / International Company News: UAP head lowers profits forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jacques Friedmann, chairman of Union des Assurances de Paris, the next
candidate for privatisation by the French government, yesterday warned that
the group's 1993 net profits were at the lower end of expectations at around
FFr1.5bn (Dollars 250m).
UAP, France's largest insurer and due within the next few weeks be sold off,
had previously forecast net profits of between FFr1.5bn and FFr2bn for last
year.
However, Mr Friedmann, a senior bureaucrat andclose friend of Mr Edouard
Balladur, the prime minister, and who last autumn became chairman of UAP
following the departure of Mr Jean Peyrelevade to the Credit Lyonnais
banking group, told shareholders in Paris that its 1993 net profits would be
'in the region of FFr1.5bn'.
UAP, like other French insurers, in recent years has been badly affected by
the competitive state of the insurance market and by the impact of the
economic recession on its property holdings and banking interests. One of
its main problems has been the poor performance of Banque Worms, its
loss-making banking subsidiary.
Net profits peaked at FFr4.22bn in 1990, but fell to FFr3.77bn in 1991 and
to FFr1.08bn in 1992. It has already reported a modest increase in interim
net profits to FFr1.09bn for the first half of last year.
However, UAP's recovery was checked in the closing months of 1993. 'The main
problems seem to have been the performance of Banque Worms and the potential
losses associated with the recent flooding in northern France,' said Mr
Derek Elias, European insurance analyst at Paribas in London.
Analysts are confident that UAP will see more robust profits growth this
year, albeit to a total well below its 1990 and 1991 levels. Mr Elias said
it should benefit from the recent rise in insurance premiums in France.
</TEXT>
