<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / International Company News: Luxottica sees a vision of world
domination  - The expansion plans of Italy's leading maker of spectacle
frames
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By  HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Few Italians would recognise Mr Leonardo Del Vecchio if they met him in the
street. Yet mention his name and most would immediately recall the modest
man from a Milan orphanage who is Italy's biggest taxpayer.
Luxottica, his company, is the world's leading maker of spectacle frames.
Its international market share is estimated at almost 9 per cent. One in
five Americans who wear glasses is a customer. In Italy, the proportion is
one in three. Though the business may seem mundane, margins are high enough
to generate net profits of L67.5bn on sales of L523bn in 1992.
Results for 1993 should be even better when released next early month.
Boosted by the lira devaluation, sales rose by about 24 per cent to more
than L640bn (Dollars 375m), while net profits should maintain the 12 per
cent growth of the previous year - in spite of recession. About
three-quarters of output is exported.
The surge in profits and turnover, which grew 8 per cent even allowing for
exchange rate changes, should also be reflected in the dividend, likely to
rise in proportion to earnings, says Mr Del Vecchio, Luxottica's founder and
controlling shareholder.
Such buoyant figures, continuing a steady growth since the company listed 25
per cent of its shares in the US in 1990, help to explain why Luxottica
remains among Italian analysts' preferred stocks.
Its prestige may grow even more if Mr Del Vecchio pulls off a number of
acquisitions believed to be in the pipeline. Although he declines to
identify the candidates, Luxottica's strong balance sheet leaves it well
placed to reinforce its international dominance through further takeovers.
Recognising the need for integration in a traditionally fragmented business
has been Luxottica's trump card. The world market for spectacle frames is
divided among dozens of companies. Now, four, led by Luxottica, which
produced 10.4m pairs in 1992, head the pack, with a myriad of smaller
manufacturers dividing the rest of the market between them.
Many smaller players seem destined to disappear as other manufacturers
follow Luxottica's path. Beginning as a sub-contractor of
delicately-engineered spectacle parts, it gradually encompassed the entire
manufacturing process for glasses in metal and plastic and wholesale
distribution in large markets.
Its international position has been consolidated by acquiring local
distributors or setting up its own distribution arm where necessary. That
has helped it capture about 22 per cent of the market in Canada, 9 per cent
in the UK and 6 per cent in France.
Early recognition of the trend towards more expensive 'designer-label'
eyewear has been its other asset.
While cheaper eyewear was left to low-cost Asian producers, it was only in
the mid-1980s that the market for dearer, Dollars 100-Dollars 350 designer
brands, was developed. Luxottica makes glasses under licence for seven
design labels, including leading lights such as Armani and Valentino.
Expansion of the core range has been accompanied by a diversification into
sunglasses. They now account for 24 per cent of sales, up from 10 per cent
when introduced five years ago.
Mr Del Vecchio denies sales and profits may have peaked. Demand in the US,
the biggest market, continues to grow. Meanwhile, spectacle-wearing in other
countries, even western Europe, is not up to US levels, while there is huge
untapped potential elsewhere, he argues. Demographics help: as populations
have grown older with improved medical care, the need for corrective lenses
has increased steadily.
He is also convinced the industry is set for further rationalisation. The
recession has accelerated the shake-out, he believes. 'Those companies which
were badly managed in terms of production and distribution, or were in poor
financial shape, have seen profits fall,' he says.
Mr Del Vecchio says gaining exclusive distribution was vital to raising
sales so sharply in the US. The focus is now on repeating that in other
developed countries where Luxottica's market share is still only about 2-4
per cent and can at least be doubled, he believes.
Product diversification is also on the cards. The designer brands still have
room for further development, he believes. Expansion into branded
sunglasses, which now account for 24 per cent of turnover, also seems
likely.
The challenge of contact lenses - once thought insuperable - is also
dismissed. The main reason why 98 per cent of US spectacles have to come
from abroad is that domestic manufacturers believed in the late 1960s that
traditional glasses had no future and concentrated instead on contact
lenses. 'Experience has shown people want both,' he says.
But perhaps the best measure of confidence in Mr Del Vecchio comes not from
the chairman or the analysts who regularly tip Luxottica's stock. As part of
the licensing deal with Armani, Mr del Vecchio included a 2 per cent stake
in the company. Since then, Mr Armani is believed to have purchased further
stock, taking his holding to almost 5 per cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Luxottica Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3851 Ophthalmic Goods.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
