<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Taking stock of the in-store format - A US
investment house is backing WEW's expansion plans.
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This month's change of title by Amber Day Holdings to WEW Group - named
after the discount retailer's chain of stores, What Everyone Wants - was
billed as marking 'a clear separation with the past'.
That aspiration was all too understandable. The Glasgow-based company has
recently been dogged by boardroom turmoil - with three chairmen in the last
16 months - and in November Pounds 9m of provisions and write-offs left the
balance sheet sadly depleted.
However, WEW might at last be entering a period of greater stability. A
placing and Pounds 15.5m rights issue last month allowed Warburg Pincus, the
US investment institution, to raise its stake in the group from 17 per cent
to 25 per cent.
The US investment house, which likes to take long-term positions, is backing
the group's aim to double the number of WEW stores to about 125 over the
next five years in the process of expanding across the whole country from
its current strongholds in Scotland, the north of England and the Midlands.
Mr Peter Carr, who took over as executive chairman in August, is confident
that WEW's distinctive formula can turn it into the leading national
discount department store chain, but accepts that rebuilding credibility
with investors will be a long haul.
He says: 'The six new stores opened since August are trading 30 per cent
ahead of budget and I am convinced we have a great opportunity to go for.'
WEW's stores - which mainly sell clothing - are fairly large, averaging
15,000 sq ft, and are aimed at the less prosperous demographic groups C2DE,
which represent 63 per cent of the UK population. However, the group's
limited regional penetration means it is currently available to only 29 per
cent of that target customer base.
Mr Carr says: 'I would like to open 20 stores within the M25.'
Analysts continue to be impressed by the underlying WEW business, which has
an operating margin of 8.7 per cent. Mr Carr believes sales are too low at
Pounds 149 per square foot - and hopes to get up to Pounds 180.
One route would be by greater use of in-store concessions - a familiar
feature of the department store format which the new management team
favours. A licensee selling costume and gold jewellery did well before
Christmas and there are similar plans to introduce concessions selling
luggage and men's suits across the group.
Warburg Pincus is backing the new management team of Mr Carr and Mr Keith
Paskins, finance director. They are both experienced retailers, having
worked together with Galerias Preciados in Spain and before that with
Debenhams.
Mr Carr concedes things are very different in WEW from the disciplines he
was used to as part of a larger group. He says: 'There was no proper
business plan or budget. We are doing the first proper inventory this month.
We've got a lot of dud stock - we know that, but we don't know how much.'
The group has now installed a 'very basic' computerised stock control
system, which - though well short of the advanced electronic point of sales
techniques used by other retailers - should give much more financial
information.
Mr Paskins said: 'The financial systems we inherited didn't even show the
profitability of individual branches.'
This lack of investment in proper systems is one reason Mr Carr is confident
that WEW will prove a money-spinner. He says the discount market has moved
on from the days when the company could rely on selling 'cabbage' - a rag
trade term for other retailers' surplus stock, seconds and manufacturers'
over-runs.
By consistently stocking a broader and more comprehensive range Mr Carr
believes he will be able to predict the group's needs and source more
products directly from manufacturers - particularly low-cost producers
overseas.
Retail analysts accept that clearing out the stock position might impact on
performance in the current year to July, but are still hoping for pre-tax
profits of about Pounds 9m.
One said: 'It seems to be a good operation, with a very beleaguered past.
One problem is that we've never been able to look the same set of guys in
the eye and find out what happened. We need a long run of solid trading
results. But any more nasty surprises and confidence would go completely.'
</TEXT>
